column1: Update CLDRFileTransformer to handle generation of updates to yue_Hans
column84:
Split out of [CLDR-9847]:

By the end of CLDR 32, we will need to update tools/java/org/unicode/cldr/tool/CLDRFileTransformer.java to handle generation of updates to the yue_Hans locale from data in the yue[_Hant] locale using the Traditional-Simplified transform. To do this we will need a new PolicyIfExisting type, which in turn will need access to the values for yue_Hant and yue_Hans in the current release (the one currently being finished when CLDRFileTransformer is run to update certain locales), as well as to the values for yue_Hant from the previous release, and probably also to the values for yue_Hans in the previous release.

I think this new PolicyIfExisting behavior should operate as follows:
* If current yue_Hans value == previous yue_Hans value (yue_Hans value not updated in this release), AND
* If current yue_Hant value != previous yue_Hant value (yue_Hant value was updated in this release), AND
* If current yue_Hans value == transform of previous yue_Hant value (yue_Hans was generated), THEN
* Set current yue_Hans value = transform of current yue_Hant value

It may be that the first condition above is effectively redundant, need to think about this some more.

Hello,

There's no tag for the latest stable version (CLDR 39) in the JSON repo: [https://github.com/unicode-org/cldr-json/releases|https://github.com/unicode-org/cldr-json/releases]. I tried creating the {{39.0.0}} tag myself but obviously I miss the rights to do so.

These JSON packages are used by many major software, e.g. Angular, Globalize...

Could any maintainer update the JSON files and tag to the latest version? Thanks in advance.

Related to:

* [https://unicode-org.atlassian.net/browse/CLDR-14317|https://unicode-org.atlassian.net/browse/CLDR-14317]
* [https://unicode-org.atlassian.net/browse/CLDR-14258|https://unicode-org.atlassian.net/browse/CLDR-14258]
* [https://unicode-org.atlassian.net/browse/CLDR-12014|https://unicode-org.atlassian.net/browse/CLDR-12014]

We should steamline the BRS tooling/process, making the items more turnkey wherever possible. There will alway need to be some human intervention in terms of reviewing the changes made by the tool, but we should eliminate as much of the 'grunt work' involved as possible.

column1: Errors from testing production data for 39-alpha4
column144: 08/Mar/21 10:19 AM;5b29558fe478c9080efacbde;Issue might be test is using CLDRFile methods that returns non-resolved string value. COuld lazily create resolved file and check that if there is an initial failure.
column145:
09/Mar/21 11:04 AM;5b29558fe478c9080efacbde;Actually neither of these issues had to do with using CLDRFile non-resolved string value.

# The first has to do with how to handle requests for display names that are both short and dialect-style (non-compound); the CLDR spec does not say which to give priority. The fr data in the main CLDR repo was as below, with the items removed as redundant for production data marked with '-'. 

{noformat}   <languages>
     <language type="en">anglais</language>
     <language type="en_GB">anglais britannique</language>
-    <language type="en_GB" alt="short">anglais (R.-U.)</language>
     <language type="en_US">anglais am√©ricain</language>
-    <language type="en_US" alt="short">anglais (√â.-U.)</language>
 
   <territories>
     <territory type="GB">Royaume-Uni</territory>
     <territory type="GB" alt="short">R.-U.</territory>
     <territory type="US">√âtats-Unis</territory>
     <territory type="US" alt="short">√â.-U.</territory>{noformat}

If we are just asking for the short dialect names for en_US or en_GB there is no issue, and the short names for en_GB/US are redundant. But if we ask for the name of something like "en_US_POSIX", they are not only non-redundant but actually harmful. We first get the dialect name for e.g. "anglais (√â.-U.)", then convert parens to square brackets, and append other variant names using the standard localeDisplayPattern.

With data in the main repo, we were getting:

{noformat}standard long:  "anglais (√âtats-Unis, informatique)"
standard short: "anglais (√â.-U., informatique)"
dialect long:   "anglais am√©ricain (informatique)"
dialect short:  "anglais [√â.-U.] (informatique)"  ** bad **{noformat}

So I decided to remove the ‚Äúshort‚Äù entries for en_US/en_GNB in the main repo (they get stripped for production data anyway). With removal we get this, same as what we were getting with production data, which is better:

{noformat}dialect short:  "anglais am√©ricain (informatique)"  ** better ** {noformat}

However for this particular case we might prefer the following, which would require a spec change to favor the request for short over the request for dialect-style (though that behavior might not be desired for all dialect-style names):

{noformat}dialect short:  "anglais (√â.-U., informatique)"   ** best for this case, maybe not others **{noformat}

----

2. The second is more of an issue with the {{TestMissingStatus}} test. It was calling VettingViewer.getMissingStatus to verify that a particular unit display name was PRESENT. However, in French, that name currently has ‚Üë‚Üë‚Üë and gets stripped for production. But even though the value ultimately comes from root in either case, VettingViewer.getMissingStatus reports PRESENT if the item is present with ‚Üë‚Üë‚Üë and ABSENT if the item is stripped. So for the test, choose another unit display item that does not have ‚Üë‚Üë‚Üë.

column1: CLONE - Review sensitive terminology in code and data files, part 2
column84:
[https://unicode-org.atlassian.net/browse/CLDR-13922|https://unicode-org.atlassian.net/browse/CLDR-13922] removed references to "grandfathered" in the CLDR spec where possible. But there are other instances of sensitive terminology in CLDR code and data that should be reviewed as well. As Markus points out in a comment for CLDR-13922: In CLDR code and in data files, there are also uses of ‚Äúgrandfathered‚Äù, ‚Äúmaster‚Äù, ‚Äúslave‚Äù, ‚Äúblacklist‚Äù, and ‚Äúcrazy‚Äù. Need to investigate these and reword as appropriate.

Note that the name of language "den" is some variant of ‚ÄúSlave‚Äù or ‚ÄúSlavey‚Äù in many locales.

This is a followup for CLDR 39 or later to investigate and address any items not handled under the original v38 ticket [https://unicode-org.atlassian.net/browse/CLDR-14226|https://unicode-org.atlassian.net/browse/CLDR-14226|smart-link]

column1: BRS A26.6 Create a simple tool to check for CLDR data that isn't converted
column84:
It is very difficult to do A26.6, so I wrote a quick and dirty tool to do a comparison.

It just finds all the values in ldml files, and sees if they are in ICU. So the test is rough, but proved useful in identifying problems.

TODO

# The current code just looks for quoted values in ICU. Should be changed to read the files with UResourceBundle. That will solve some mismatches because of formatting.
# It could be extended to JSON, reading the JSON files instead of ICU. The only thing we need is a bit of code that extracts all the values from a JSON file.
# The inputs are hard-coded, and should use command-line arguments instead.
# etc.

This can't be a unit test, because it works off of the cldr-staging production files, and the ICU data built from them.

column1: BRS A05.7 - TSV generation with charts instead of compare en.java
column84:
BRS A05.7 task:
* Analyze differences between en_GB and en_001 (main and annotations), determine which data needs to move up to en_001 and any necessary corrections.

To generate files for comparison, currently requires running "Compare en.java" locally.

Could be moved to TSV, and be done in parallel to charts creation.

Look into adding TSV generation to charts, and run once in the background.

column1: BRS Fix unit tests for cldr-staging/production
column84:
I made a test run on cldr-staging/production (-DCLDR_DIR=.../cldr-staging/production). No showstoppers for v36, but issues that we should address in v37.

1. I had to add empty directories for the following. A more permanent test would be to modify the unit-tests to not depend on those directories in production data/exemplars/seed/¬† annotations/
¬† casing/
¬† collation/
¬† main/
¬† rbnf/
¬† transforms/


2. AnnotationsCLDR/TestAnnotations/testAnnotationPaths
CLDR/TestAnnotations/testEmojiImages
CLDR/TestAnnotations/testSuperfluousAnnotationPathsAll of the above appear to because the annotations/root.xml file is empty (correctly, for production data). So that also needs a test tweak.


3. CLDR/TestDisplayAndInputProcessor/TestAdlamNasalizationThe test is for a particular file in seed/, which doesn't exist. So that also needs a test tweak.


4. CLDR/TestInheritance/TestLikelyAndDefaultConsistency
Not sure what this one is from. Looks like a test problem, though.

column1: CLDRTransforms needs to preserve ‚Üë‚Üë‚Üë for logical groups
column84: CLDRTransforms does not "copy over" `‚Üë‚Üë‚Üë` items.  This is especially a problem where logical grouping is concerned.
column144:
24/Aug/21 3:01 PM;5af4a8718a1abd1427952ed9;To work around the issue, see for example [https://github.com/unicode-org/cldr/pull/1463/commits/adebffe67d757efa860fc32f3b1c99926aaa3d16|https://github.com/unicode-org/cldr/pull/1463/commits/adebffe67d757efa860fc32f3b1c99926aaa3d16|smart-link] 



* In a typical locale, changing one item in a group requires voting for the ‚Üë‚Üë‚Üë which make up the group.
* CLDRTransforms ought to mimic this by adding such ‚Üë‚Üë‚Üë entries as are needed.
Alternatively, just copy over _all_ items, including triple up arrow.

column1: BRS Misc. fixes to LDML spec
column84:
This is for various fixes that aren't included in other LDML spec tickets. A major  goal is to cover all the new DTD structure in [https://unicode-org.github.io/cldr-staging/charts/38/supplemental/dtd_deltas.html|https://unicode-org.github.io/cldr-staging/charts/38/supplemental/dtd_deltas.html], and fix other problems noticed while doing that.

People can add comments to this issue as they find problems. Please include link to the section where the problem is. Current modifications are in:

[https://unicode-org.github.io/cldr/ldml/tr35.html#Modifications|https://unicode-org.github.io/cldr/ldml/tr35.html#Modifications]
column144:

column144: 12/Aug/20 2:37 PM;5ecea98db1df560c072c4268;[~accountid:5b1fa41abe73de20759a87c2] Since Peter is out, reassigning to Mark
column145:
15/Aug/20 2:18 PM;5b1fa41abe73de20759a87c2;Expanded Recommendations

On the CLDR side:

# We already have Sanskrit and Dogri on our list to move to common, as above.
# Move Caddo and Guarani out of the CLDR target locales.
## They are already in seed, and were added as CLDR target locales when we thought we were going to do them.
# Move Church Slavic, Prussian, Volap√ºk from common to seed.
## Some marked as common have very low Basic _and_ are not in ICU.
## Document in the Migration section

On the ICU side:

# Add common CLDR that are missing in ICU (after above cases): Nigerian Pidgin, Sundanese, Sanskrit, Dogri, Manipuri, Maithili, Santali, Sindhi (Devanagari), Fulah (Adlam) go into ICU.
# Remove very low-stat, non common locales: Low German

----

This is *_just_* for this release, and continuing past principles. We have two conjoined goals longer term:

# Move the seed locales into the common directory.
# Replace the "seed" vs "common" distinction by new coverage levels. That is, we would reorganize our coverage levels so that there is a category for "ready for ICU", where 100% qualifies and anything less doesn't. That would make the "decide what goes into ICU" pretty much turn-key. We may decide to retrofit Basic to fill this need, or may put something below Basic.

----

See also [https://unicode-org.github.io/cldr-staging/charts/38/supplemental/locale_coverage.html|https://unicode-org.github.io/cldr-staging/charts/38/supplemental/locale_coverage.html]

09/May/19 12:42 PM;5b34954eddd2363f63053eec;h6. Trac Comment 2 by [~accountid:5b1fa41abe73de20759a87c2]‚Äî2019-02-11T12:47:07.161Z
We currently lose the information that the inheritance marker was approved, which loses the information we need to do the right thing for coverage / logical groups. [this has been an issue for a while, but smaller in scope so we didn't notice it; by improving the way we handle inheritance markers, we have just brought it to light.|Background:]

To do that need to output the inheritance marker (for winning values!) into vxml. We can then process it as needed to deal with the logical groupings and coverage. So here's my plan.

I looked at the cldr-apps code, and it looks like that is easy to do in OutputFileManager.java. (Thanks to John and/or Steve for the foresight...). It is to make the following change (just deleting the "SUPPRESS_IM").

OLD
    Map<String, Object> OPTS_SKIP_ANNOTATIONS = ImmutableMap.of("SUPPRESS_IM", true,

        "SKIP_PATH", isAnnotations);

    Map<String, Object> OPTS_KEEP_ANNOTATIONS = ImmutableMap.of("SUPPRESS_IM", true,

        "SKIP_PATH", isAnnotations.negate());

NEW
    Map<String, Object> OPTS_SKIP_ANNOTATIONS = ImmutableMap.of(

        "SKIP_PATH", isAnnotations);

    Map<String, Object> OPTS_KEEP_ANNOTATIONS = ImmutableMap.of(

        "SKIP_PATH", isAnnotations.negate());


That eventually causes CLDRFile.write(PrintWriter pw, Map<String, ?> options) to *not* skip the inheritance markers.

So I'd do the following.
## Make this change and push to production
## Pull down the vxml data again
## Write a simple tool
### for each directory, for each locale's file, for each missing item in trunk data
### get the vxml value. If it is ‚Üë‚Üë‚Üë, then add the Bailey value to the file.
## Run tests, regenerate coverage, etc. and check in.
## File a ticket for next release to modify that tool as appropriate so that we can automate the handling of ‚Üë‚Üë‚Üë when pulling the vxml data into trunk
